flowRoot.flowPara: INTRODUCTION

Thermoelectric materials have the potential to revolutionise and optimise all electricity generation and cooling methods. They are both simple to use and incredibly reliable; apply a heat gradient for electricity, apply electricity for cooling. Currently, their efficiency limits applications to space probes, where their reliability is most important. But with the potential advancements of nanocomposite design, we could see utilisation in heat recovery systems, refridgeration and solar thermal generation.

In this project, we have attempted a full theoretical analysis of a spherical SiGe nanocomposite, optimising key parameters and minimising inaccuracies as we progress. So far we understand that, small nanometer scale silicon spheres, densely packed in a n-doped germanium host has the potential to improve the thermoelectric efficiency 10x; with this improvement, the applications listed above become feasible.
ABSTRACT

THERMOELECTRICITY

In any material, heat is conducted via two carriers, phonons and electrons. Thermoelectricity is simply a heat induced electrical gradient, whereby charge carriers are carried from either side of the thermal gradient.
